3. Interest Charges, Rates, And Fees
3.1. An Interest Charge will be imposed on a Previous Balance whenever any portion of the Previous Balance shown on the current billing statement remains unpaid after the due date shown on the previous billing statement.  In addition, an Interest Charge will be imposed on new Purchases that are posted for the first time on your current billing statement if there was a Previous Balance on the prior billing statement and the payments and credits received by us by the due date shown on the previous billing statement did not at least equal the Previous Balance.  If New Purchases are subject to Interest, Interest will be charged from the date the New Purchase is posted to your Account.  Interest will be calculated using the Daily Balance Method.  To determine the Daily Balance subject to Interest Charges, we start with the balance on your Account (including Purchases, accrued Interest Charges and other charges) as of the end of the previous day, and we add any interest for such day and any New Purchases.  We then subtract any payments, credits and outstanding disputes posted that day plus any other adjustments. This gives us the Daily Balance.  We then multiply the Daily Balance by the applicable Daily Periodic Rate.  We do this for each day in the Billing Cycle.  Then we add up all the Daily Interest for all of the Daily Balances in the Billing Cycle to get the total interest.  
3.2. Penalty Interest Charge on Purchases: In the event you fail to make any Minimum Payment by the payment Due Date or a payment you make is returned (each a “Default Event”), the Daily Periodic Rate and the corresponding APR in effect for all outstanding charges (including Statement Balances, and other transactions) may increase to a Penalty Rate from their standard, non-penalty rate or any introductory or promotional rate. The Penalty Rate will apply as of the first day of the next billing cycle after the default event occurred. Company must be “current” on all payments for consecutive billing cycles in order for the Penalty Rate to cease being charged.  The number of consecutive billing cycles that Company must be current in its payments in order for the Penalty Rate to cease to apply is disclosed in the Rate Chart.  On the first day of the billing cycle following that period, the APR on your account will revert to the standard, non-penalty APR, but not any introductory or promotional rates.
3.3. Variable Rate. If your account is a variable rate account, the APR may vary each month based on changes in the Index.  An increase in the Index may result in a higher Minimum Payment.  The variable ANNUAL PERCENTAGE RATE will be based on the Index plus a Margin.  You will be advised whether your Account is subject to a variable rate.  
3.4. Non-Variable Rate. The Daily Periodic Rate for Purchase transactions subject to the Non-Variable Rate will be based on an ANNUAL PERCENTAGE RATE that does not vary with changes in an Index.  You will be advised whether your Account is subject to a fixed (non-variable) rate.
3.5. Interest Charges On Promotional Balances. From time to time we may offer you a Promotional Rate on certain Purchase balances that arise from new transactions we tell you will be treated as “Promotional Balances.”  If you take advantage of a Promotional Balance offer, the resulting Promotional Balance will be subject to the terms of that specific promotional offer and this Agreement.  The Promotional Rate will apply to those Promotional Balances until the termination date for the offer.  A Promotional Balance may not, after a termination date, be eligible for another Promotional Rate.  Beginning on the first day of a Billing Cycle following a termination date, the Daily Periodic Rate applied to Promotional Balances will be determined as described above.  If the reason for the Termination Date is a delinquency triggering event, we may change the Interest Rate that applies to your new and outstanding Promotional Balances to the Penalty Interest Charge, as described above.  In each Promotional Balance offer, any new or different terms of the program not disclosed in this Agreement (such as the Annual Percentage Rate, effective dates and other special terms) will be detailed in a separate writing.
3.6. Minimum Interest Charges. If Interest Charges are billed in any Billing Cycle, a Minimum Interest Charge as set forth in the Rate Chart will post to your Account (a minimum interest charge shown as the “Minimum Interest Charge” on your billing statements). We may allocate the Minimum Interest Charge among your various balances in the manner that we select from time to time. 
3.7. Index Adjustments.  The Index used in making variable rate adjustments to your APR will be the Prime Rate as quoted in the "Money Rates" section of The Wall Street Journal (Eastern Edition) as of the last day of your billing cycle, or if this day is a non-business day, then the last Business Day before the close of the billing cycle.  To determine the APR that applies to your Account, we will add the Margin, as disclosed on the Rate Chart.  The applicable Prime Rate plus Margin on the last day of each billing cycle will be the APR that is applied to your Account for that entire billing cycle and will remain in effect until a change in the Index results in an adjustment to the APR, as provided herein.  An Index increase will increase the applicable Daily Periodic Rates, which may increase your Minimum Payment.
3.8. Other Charges That May Be Imposed.  Except where prohibited by applicable law, the fees set forth in the Rate Chart, as applicable, or as otherwise agreed to by the parties, may be added to your Account.  
4. Payment Requirements; Minimum Payment.  Company must pay us in United States dollars, using checks or similar payment instruments drawn on a financial institution located in the United States.  Payments received by 3:30 p.m. are credited as of the date of receipt.  All other payments are credited as of the next Business Day. The date you mail a payment is different than the date we process that payment.  
4.1 Company agrees to pay and/or perform:  (i) fees listed on the attached fee schedule; (ii) all amounts payable for Transactions on each Card or Account; (iii) any and all costs (including reasonable attorneys’ fees) incurred by Issuer in enforcing Company’s obligations in this Agreement; and (iv) all obligations, covenants, and warranties in this Agreement.  
4.2. Your payment due date is set forth in the Rate Chart If the payment due date falls on a non-Business Day, then payment is due on the Business Day before the due date. Based upon Issuer’s credit review, Company may be required to make payment more frequently or may elect a shorter billing or payment cycle.  In that event, Company will receive alternate terms in writing.  
4.3. Each Guarantor signing the credit application and/or this Agreement, unconditionally, jointly, and severally guarantees the full and prompt payment of all amounts due and owing at any time.  Guarantor hereby waives claims and defenses based on principles of surety ship or other applicable law as a guarantor.  Each Guarantor agrees to comply with the notification procedures defined herein. 
4.4. Company has the option of paying in full the Statement Balance shown on each billing statement or paying it in installments, as long as Company pays at least the Minimum Payment shown on the billing statement.  
To calculate your Minimum Payment due, WEX shall use the following formula:
 [(Prior Statement Balance + Current Period Purchases + Current Period Credits and Debits)*2%] + (Current Period Interest + Current Period Fees + Any Over Credit Limit Amounts + Past Due Minimum Payment Amounts) = Minimum Payment Due
If the total Statement Balance is less than $30.00, the Minimum Payment will equal the total Statement Balance.  If you pay more than the Minimum Payment, you still must make the Minimum Payment on subsequent billing statements until you have fully paid what you owe.
4.5. Company agrees that the Minimum Payments on your Account may be applied in the order we select.  We may allocate your Minimum Payments to balances starting with the lowest Annual Percentage Rate.  Payments you make in excess of the Minimum Payment will generally be applied first to balances with the lowest Annual Percentage Rate and any remaining portion to the other balances in ascending order based on their Annual Percentage Rates, unless we are required by law to use a different payment application method in connection with a deferred interest or similar program.  Payments are normally applied to restore your available credit (the amount of your unused Company Credit Limit).  There may be a delay in restoring your available credit until we determine whether a payment is unlikely to be returned for insufficient funds or for some other reason.
